---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import GalleryBox from "../components/GalleryBox.astro";
import treeNodeHangingOrum from "../assets/tree-node-hanging-Orum.jpg";
import treeNodeHangingW1SCO from "../assets/tree-node-hanging-W1SCO.jpg";
---

<Layout
	title="Build a Node"
	description="Learn how to build a Madison Mesh node — from choosing hardware and enclosures to solar power and secure mounting."
>
	<div class="container">
		<section class="section">
			<h1>Build a Node</h1>
			<p>
				A "node" is just a LoRa radio with the right firmware, a good antenna, and a power source. You can
				have a basic indoor node running in under an hour, or build a weatherproof solar-powered outdoor
				node that runs for years with no maintenance. Many amazing pre-built options are also available.
			</p>
			<p>This page covers common builds from simplest to most capable. Start wherever makes sense for you.</p>
		</section>

		<hr class="divider" />

		<!-- Build types -->
		<section class="section">
			<h2>Which Type of Node?</h2>

			<div class="card-grid">
				<div class="card">
					<span class="card-icon">🏠</span>
					<h3>Indoor / Window Node</h3>
					<p style="font-size:0.95rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem;">
						The simplest possible node. A LoRa radio plugged into a USB charger, placed in an
						upper-floor window with the stock or a short external antenna.
					</p>
					<p class="text-muted" style="font-size:0.85rem; margin-bottom: 0;">
						<strong>Cost:</strong> $15–$50 &bull; <strong>Range:</strong> 0.5–3 mi &bull; <strong
							>Resilience:</strong
						> Low; vulnerable to cats and power outages
					</p>
				</div>
				<div class="card">
					<span class="card-icon">🔌</span>
					<h3>Outdoor / Wired Node</h3>
					<p style="font-size:0.95rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem;">
						Radio in a weatherproof enclosure mounted outside, powered via a USB or PoE cable from
						indoors. Best range improvement for the cost.
					</p>
					<p class="text-muted" style="font-size:0.85rem; margin-bottom: 0;">
						<strong>Cost:</strong> $50+ &bull; <strong>Range:</strong> 2–10+ mi &bull; <strong
							>Resilience:</strong
						> Strong to weather, but vulnerable to power outages
					</p>
				</div>
				<div class="card">
					<span class="card-icon">☀️</span>
					<h3>Solar / Off-Grid Node</h3>
					<p style="font-size:0.95rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem;">
						A fully self-contained node with solar panel, LiPo battery, and MPPT charge controller.
						Can be placed anywhere with sunlight — no power outlet needed.
					</p>
					<p class="text-muted" style="font-size:0.85rem; margin-bottom: 0;">
						<strong>Cost:</strong> $30+ &bull; <strong>Range:</strong> 2–10+ mi &bull;
						<strong>Resilience:</strong> Strong to weather and power outages
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<hr class="divider" />

		<!-- Parts list -->
		<section class="section">
			<h2>What You Need</h2>

			<h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">The Radio</h3>
			<p>For solar nodes, choose the most power-efficient options first. Recommended order:</p>
			<ul style="color: var(--clr-light); padding-left: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; line-height: 2;">
				<li>
					Rak Meshtastic Starter Kit (<a
						href="https://store.rokland.com/products/rak-wireless-wisblock-meshtastic-starter-kit#"
						target="_blank">regular</a
					> and <a
						href="https://store.rokland.com/products/rakwireless-mini-meshtastic-starter-kit-us915-rak19003-4631-sku-115093"
						target="_blank">mini</a
					>)
				</li>
				<li>
					<a
						href="https://www.seeedstudio.com/XIAO-nRF52840-Wio-SX1262-Kit-for-Meshtastic-p-6400.html"
						target="_blank">Seeed XIAO nRF52840 &amp; Wio-SX1262 Kit</a
					>
				</li>
				<li>
					<a href="https://heltec.org/project/mesh-node-t114/" target="_blank">Heltec T114</a>
				</li>
			</ul>
			<p class="text-muted">
				For non-solar nodes, use <a href="https://heltec.org/project/wifi-lora-32-v4/" target="_blank"
					>Heltec V4</a
				>.
			</p>

			<h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Antenna</h3>
			<p>
				See the <a href="/coverage">Coverage &amp; Antennas</a> page for a full breakdown, or visit the
				<a href="https://meshtastic.org/docs/hardware/antennas/">Meshtastic Antennas Guide</a> for specific model
				recommendations. For most fixed nodes, any <strong>3–5 dBi 915 MHz fiberglass omni antenna </strong> is
				a good choice ($10–$25 on Amazon). Make sure the connector matches your radio (usually RP-SMA or SMA female).
			</p>

			<h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Enclosure (outdoor builds)</h3>
			<p class="reduced-bottom">For outdoor use your radio must be protected from moisture. Common options:</p>
			<ul style="color: var(--clr-light); padding-left: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; line-height: 2;">
				<li>
					<a
						href="https://www.amazon.com/TICONN-Waterproof-Electrical-Junction-Enclosure/dp/B0BZR3GZ4V?th=1"
						>TICONN ABS junction box</a
					>: cheap and widely available, comes in sizes to fit most boards. Use cable glands for wire
					entry.
				</li>
				<li>
					<a
						href="https://www.instructables.com/Meshtastic-Harbor-Breeze-Solar-Node/"
						target="_blank"
						rel="noopener noreferrer">Meshtastic Harbor Breeze Solar Node</a
					>: a popular DIY solar node design with 3D-printed parts and off-the-shelf components. Great
					for stealthy, HOA-compliant builds.
				</li>
				<li>
					<strong>3D-printed enclosures</strong>: community members share designs. PETG or ASA plastic
					handles outdoor UV and temperature. Take extra precautions to ensure these are fully sealed
					against water ingress.
				</li>
				<li>
					<strong>Commercial outdoor IoT cases</strong>: RAK makes enclosures designed specifically for
					their WisBlock modules, and other companies make similar cases for popular boards.
					<a href="https://www.iot-bots.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">iot-bots.com</a>
					is a good source for these.
				</li>
			</ul>

			<h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Power</h3>
			<ul style="color: var(--clr-light); padding-left: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; line-height: 2;">
				<li>
					<strong>Indoor / wired:</strong> Any 5V USB power adapter. A small lithium battery can add hours
					of backup.
				</li>
				<li>
					<strong>Solar:</strong> A 3–10W solar panel, a 2000–10000 mAh Li-Ion or LiFePo4 battery, and a small
					MPPT solar charge controller (e.g., CN3791-based modules). Most radios have a built-in charging circuit,
					however, the charging speed is often slow.
				</li>
			</ul>

			<div
				class="card"
				style="margin-top: 1.5rem; background-color: oklch(22% 0.06 232.69); border-color: var(--clr-primary-darker);"
			>
				<h3 style="color: var(--clr-primary);">💬 Community tip</h3>
				<p style="margin-bottom: 0;">
					The Madison Mesh Discord has a <strong>#building</strong> channel where members share their specific
					builds, enclosure choices, and what's working well in Wisconsin's climate. If you're unsure what
					to buy, ask there first!
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<hr class="divider" />

		<!-- Step by step build -->
		<section class="section">
			<h2>Building an Outdoor Node (Step by Step)</h2>
			<p>
				This is the build we recommend for most community members who want to make a real impact on network
				coverage. It's more capable than an indoor node, and can run indefinitely if set up with solar
				power.
			</p>

			<div class="steps">
				<div class="step">
					<div class="step-number">1</div>
					<div class="step-body">
						<h3>Flash firmware</h3>
						<p>
							Before boxing everything up, flash and configure your radio indoors first. See the
							<a href="/getting-started">Getting Started</a> guide for firmware flashing instructions.
							Test that it connects to the Madison Mesh channel and can see other nodes.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="step">
					<div class="step-number">2</div>
					<div class="step-body">
						<h3>Prepare the enclosure</h3>
						<p>
							Drill or cut holes for the antenna connector and USB cable entry. Use cable glands to
							seal around any wire penetrations. Silicone sealant around edges can add extra
							weather protection. Avoid drilling on the top of the box, as water may eventually
							drip inside. Drill on the bottom or sides so water doesn't collect around entries.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="step">
					<div class="step-number">3</div>
					<div class="step-body">
						<h3>Mount the radio inside</h3>
						<p>
							Secure the radio inside the box using double-sided foam tape, a 3D-printed bracket,
							or short standoffs. Leave enough slack in the antenna pigtail to close the box
							easily. Add a desiccant packet to absorb any moisture that sneaks in.
							<br />
							<br />
							<i
								>Warning: Some adhesives are strong and can pull components off of the PCB if
								removed later.</i
							>
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="step">
					<div class="step-number">4</div>
					<div class="step-body">
						<h3>Connect power and test</h3>
						<p>
							<strong
								>Check the polarity of ALL power connections, and never solder or connect wires
								while any power is plugged in.</strong
							> Test your solar panel in direct sunlight with a multimeter to confirm it's putting out
							the expected voltage before connecting it to your radio. Rak WisBlock boards cannot exceed
							5.5V on the solar input, for example. Once you are certain that the voltage and polarity
							are correct, connect your power source and test that the node powers on and connects to
							another node. If using solar, make sure the battery is charging properly.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="step">
					<div class="step-number">5</div>
					<div class="step-body">
						<h3>Mount the enclosure and antenna</h3>
						<p>
							Now that you know your radio is function, strategically locate a spot to mount your
							radio. Be sure to account for future wind and snow loads! Mount the box to a mast,
							pole, eave, or wall using U-bolts, hose clamps, zip ties, or stainless screws. Mount
							the antenna with its base at or above the roofline — the higher, the better. Keep the
							antenna coax run as short as possible.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>

			<GalleryBox
				images={[
					{
						src: treeNodeHangingOrum.src,
						alt: "Tree-mounted mesh node enclosure",
					},
					{
						src: treeNodeHangingW1SCO.src,
						alt: "Hanging outdoor mesh node installed in a tree",
					},
				]}
			/>
		</section>

		<hr class="divider" />

		<section class="section">
			<h2>Node configuration tips</h2>
			<p>
				Once your node is online, set it to the correct <strong>role</strong> for its purpose:
			</p>
			<h4>Meshtastic roles</h4>
			<ul style="color: var(--clr-light); padding-left: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; line-height: 2;">
				<li>
					<strong>Client</strong> — best for mobile/handheld nodes. Relays messages unless configured not to.
				</li>
				<li>
					<strong>Client</strong> — best for saving battery life. Does not relay any messages.
				</li>
				<li>
					<strong>Client Base</strong> — best for fixed nodes, prioritizes messages from nodes in its favorite
					list.
				</li>
				<li>
					<strong>Router</strong> — do not use router. It hurts the network in 99% of cases.
				</li>
			</ul>
			<h4>MeshCore roles</h4>
			<p>
				For MeshCore, repeaters are the only nodes that relay messages, and companions are the only nodes
				that can send messages. Set fixed nodes to repeater, and handheld nodes to companion.
				<br />
				<br />
				If you are setting up a repeater, check the repeater list below and make sure that your node's public
				key is not going to conflict with an existing repeater. Conflicts are based on the first two characters
				(e.x. BA) of the public key. Use <a href="https://gessaman.com/mc-keygen/"
					>gessaman's key generator</a
				>.
			</p>
			<iframe
				src="https://msn.meshmapper.net/embed_repeaters.php?mode=dark"
				width="100%"
				height="500"
				style="border: none;"
				loading="lazy"
			>
			</iframe>
			<br />
			<br />
			<h4>Final steps</h4>
			<p>
				<a href="https://config.meshcore.dev/">MeshCore configuration tool</a> &bull; <a
					href="https://meshtastic.org/docs/configuration/">Meshtastic documentation</a
				> &bull;
				<a href="https://discord.gg/fd3JUZc2CN">Ask questions on Discord</a>
			</p>
		</section>
	</div>
</Layout>
